          <text>
            The third morning comes with bittersweet awareness—last day with Streamwalker and Brightbloom. I pack my things at the reed-platform shelter, watching the guides prepare for the final stretch. Streamwalker's vines move with their usual flowing grace—testing the morning air—while Brightbloom's flowers glow in the early light, already blooming enthusiastically.

            Three days together—not long, but enough to learn their rhythms, their voices, their way of working as a team. And now it will end.

            ¶

            But this time I know it's coming—I've been expecting it—the pattern is clear now.

            Streamwalker asks, "Ready?" [Their voice is musical, carrying gentle awareness.]

            I say, "Yeah. Let's walk."

            Streamwalker and Brightbloom walk.

            The wetlands in morning light are beautiful—water reflecting pink and orange sky, flowers opening with the sun, birds—or whatever they are—calling in reed clusters. Everything alive and bright and temporary—like the guides.

            Streamwalker says, "The boundary is about two hours ahead—easy walking. The ground firms up approaching Territory Three."

            Brightbloom adds, "Less water there—more hills and rocks, completely different terrain! The Territory Three guides are excellent with elevation and stone-based navigation—very skilled!" [Brightbloom bounces encouragingly.]

            Scout bounces alongside, apparently unaware that another farewell approaches—or maybe Scout understands better than I do; connections can be real and temporary simultaneously, valued for what they are rather than mourned for what they aren't.

            I say, "I learned a lot from you two—the river crossing, the flower communication, the way you work together—calm and energy balancing each other. It's been really good."

            Brightbloom's flowers bloom brighter. Brightbloom says, "You've been an excellent traveler—very adaptable, asking good questions, handling challenges well! We'll tell the Territory Three guides how wonderful you are!"

            Streamwalker adds, "You found your pace—trust in the journey. That's rare for new travelers. Most fight the current."

            I say, "I had good teachers—in both territories."

            We walk through changing landscape. The ground does firm up—less water, more solid earth mixed with wetland soil. Different plants appear, species transitioning between territories—the boundary approaches.

            I say, "Can I ask something?"

            Brightbloom says, "Always!" [Brightbloom bounces with encouragement.]

            I say, "Do you get attached to travelers? To the people you guide?"

            There is a pause—Streamwalker's vines undulate thoughtfully—Brightbloom's flowers open and close in the pattern I have learned means 'considering response.'

            Streamwalker says, "Yes—each traveler is different. Each journey unique. The time together matters, even knowing it's temporary. Water flows through—you can't hold it—but the flowing still changes the riverbed."
          </text>
