        <chunk>
          <text>
            Then Brightbloom does something unexpected—they roll forward and very gently bump against my leg, a flower-bush hug.

            Brightbloom says [bright, wobbling slightly], "Travel well! Reach Elder Heartwood! Find your answers! *Be wonderful!*"

            I say, "You too—help more travelers. Keep the enthusiasm. It really does help, even when it's exhausting."

            Brightbloom's entire structure glows with pleasure.

            I turn to Streamwalker; the tall vine-plant stands flowing and serene as always.

            I say, "Thank you—for the calm, for teaching me to trust the current."

            Streamwalker extends one vine—not to help me walk, not to rescue me from a swamp hole—just… contact—connection.

            I take the vine gently.

            Streamwalker says [softly], "The river flows. You flow with it. Remember that in the hills—different terrain, same principle. Find the path of least resistance. Trust the guides who know the land."

            I say, "I will."

            The vine retracts.

            Streamwalker and Brightbloom turn back toward Territory Two—toward wetlands and rivers and water-based plants waiting for their guides to return.

            Brightbloom calls [already moving], "*Safe travels!* Tell everyone you meet that you crossed wetlands with Streamwalker and Brightbloom—we'll remember you!"

            Streamwalker raises a vine—one last wave—and then they disappear into the wetlands, flowing and bouncing, calm and energy, a balanced pair returning home.

            ¶

            I stand at the boundary feeling… okay.

            Sad, yes—I'll miss them: Streamwalker's musical wisdom, Brightbloom's enthusiastic encouragement. But not devastated, not lost.

            Because I understand now—this is how it works: temporary teams, real connections, necessary endings.

            And the journey continues.

            Oakshade asks [patient strength], "Ready—Territory Three is hillier. More climbing, less water. But the views are worth it."

            Mossmantle adds [soft, earthy], "And the stone formations are beautiful—very different from wetlands. You'll adapt."

            Scout bounces once, then rolls toward the new guides, already investigating.

            I take a breath and look back once at the wetlands—bright and beautiful and already past—then forward to Territory Three, hills visible in the distance, new terrain waiting.

            I say, "Yeah—I'm ready."

            Oakshade moves forward with steady grace. Mossmantle rolls smoothly beside them. Scout bounces ahead, enthusiastic as always.

            And I follow.

            New guides. New territory. New challenges. Same journey.

            I'd learned to trust Leafwhisper's cascading information and Rootwalker's grounded silence. I'd learned to trust Streamwalker's flowing calm and Brightbloom's bouncing energy.

            Now I'll learn to trust Oakshade and Mossmantle—learn their rhythms, their voices, their way of working together.

            And in three days I'll say goodbye to them too—and keep going.

            Because that is the pattern—territory by territory, team by team, one impossible adaptation at a time.
          </text>
